Today is the 50th Anniversary of Stonewall. In a piece for @Bust_Magazine @ZoNaseef wrote: ‚ÄúIt is commonly known that #Pride started with the 1969 Stonewall Inn Riots against police brutality. What is often left out of this narrative is that it was spearheaded by two transgender sex workers of color‚ÄîMarsha P. Johnson & Sylvia Rivera. According to the Global Network of Sex Work Projects (NSWP), the Stonewall Inn was commonly raided by the police because it was a notorious hangout for sex workers, trans people of color & other marginalized people.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Following the riot, Johnson & Rivera co-founded the organization Street Transvestite Action Revolutionaries, a group dedicated to helping homeless young drag queens & trans women of color. Both of their lives were dedicated to fighting for equal rights through any means necessary.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Although she had spearheaded of the movement, Rivera had to fight to speak during a 1973 pride rally because, as Melinda Chateauvert writes in her book Sex Workers Unite, ‚ÄúThe crowd did not want to hear from a transgender sex worker.‚Äù Rivera & other sex workers joined Gay Liberation Front in an attempt to create a coalition of leftist queer folk. GLF fought for the sexual revolution & an anti-capitalist agenda to combat violence & discrimination against the LGBTQ community.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
In Prostitution Papers, Kate Millet writes ‚ÄúProstitution, homosexuality & abortion are 3 instances where the law infringed upon sexual freedom.‚Äù Bringing issues together to form umbrella groups for activism is often essential in creating the space for change, as well-known trans activist @JuliaSerano wrote in her book Outspoken‚Äù Full article by @ZoNaseef: bit.ly/BustSW
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
@3WaveFund launched the Sex Worker Giving Circle with the dual goal of funding a diverse range of sex worker-led groups throughout the country & bringing current & former sex workers to the philanthropic decision-making table. This week we are talking about women's sexual health, as it is an important but very taboo part of women's overall wellbeing. While we normally have no problem talking about sexual health in terms of men, thinking about sexual health for women still seems to require a lot of sensitivity. so before we dive into all that fun stuff, we first need to talk about another important thing women face with their sexual health- slut shaming. ‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

We need to empower one another and provide a safe space to talk about sex for women.
